result.execSummary:
The defendant Renia Marie Stehofsky was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • Operating While Revoked (Rev due to alc/contr subst/refusal), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 343.44(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Renia Marie Stehofsky in court with attorney Victoria Mccandless.  Defendant Renia Marie Stehofsky in custody.  Brandon A Wigley appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
AS TO COUNT 1 & 2 - 
The defendant was advised of her constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Jury Instructions and Addendum to Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.
AS TO COUNT 1
Court ordered defendant to serve 12 MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive to any sentence; release for the Day Reporting Center and inmate work assignments; credit for 22 days time served. Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring.
Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on probation for 18 MONTHS with the below conditions. 
AS TO COUNT 2
Court ordered defendant to serve 20 DAYS in the House of Correction, concurrent to Count 1 and consecutive to any other sentence; release for the Day Reporting Center and inmate work assignments; credit for 20 days time served. Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring.
- Provide DNA sample, if not already done. 

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION AS TO COUNT 1:
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety, no alcohol.
- No use or possession of alcohol or controlled substances without a valid 
  prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  and successfully complete recommended treatment
  including drug and alcohol testing. 
- Defendant must attend at least 1 Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  treatment or sobriety support group per week for the first 3 months. After the first 3 months       
  Defendant to attend at least 1 Alcohol and Drug Assessment  treatment or sobriety support group per 
  month.
-Defendant to notify Department of Corrections agent of all prescriptions within 72 hours of receiving prescription from any Doctor.
- Fill all prescriptions at one pharmacy, unless otherwise approved by Department of Corrections Agent, and notify the Department of Corrections agent of the pharmacy used. 
 - No possession of any drug paraphernalia for personal use, manufacturing, delivering or for distribution.
- No possession of any firearms or weapons, firearm ammunition, firearm holster, firearm magazine, or any body armor.
- Seek and maintain full time work and/or school as physically and mentally able per the Department of Corrections.
- Complete a Parenting course.
- Mental Health Evaluation and any recommended treatment. Court recommends Trauma Informed Mental Health Treatment. 
- No driving without valid driving privileges.
-Court orders 21 days of condition time, without good time credit, release for inmate work assignments, and the Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring. 
-Court imposes and stays 105 days of condition time, without good time credit, release for inmate work assignments, and with a strong objection to electronic monitoring. Condition time to be imposed by the Department of Corrections as follows:
*30 days for 1st positive drug or alcohol test,
*35 days for a 2nd positive drug or alcohol test,
*40 days for a 3rd positive drug or alcohol test.
- Provide DNA sample, if not already done. 

AS TO COUNT 1 & 2:
Pay all mandatory court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including the DNA surcharge, during the course of probation to the probation agent. Any remaining balance due at the end of probation will become immediately due or civil judgment to be entered. 


Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.

Appellate rights notice given to the defendant. 
Filed;

Court orders the Defendant make all mandatory Court appearances in all pending cases. Failure to comply with conditions of bail may result in an additional charge of bail jumping.
